{{Infobox NBA biography | name = Rolando Hourruitiner | image = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1975|05|28}} | birth_place = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] | nationality = Puerto Rico (USA) | career_start = 1992 | career_end = 2006 | years1 = 1992–1995 | team1 = [[Leones de Ponce (basketball)|Leones de Ponce]] | years2 = 1996–1997 | team2 = [[Cariduros de Fajardo]] | years3 = 1998 | team3 = [[Gallitos de Isabela]] | years4 = 1999–2006 | team4 = [[Cangrejeros de Santurce (basketball)|Cangrejeros de Santurce]] | coach_start =2009 | coach_end =2015 | cyears1 = | cteam1 = | awards = * 6× Player [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional|BSN]] Champion (1992, 1993, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003) * 1× Head Coach [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional|BSN]] Coach of the Year (2010) | medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{bk|PUR}}}} {{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}} {{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA AmeriCup]]}} {{MedalBronze| [[FIBA Americas Championship 2003|2003 San Juan]] | }} {{MedalCompetition|[[Centrobasket]]}} {{MedalSilver| [[2004 Centrobasket|2004 Santo Domingo]] | }} {{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Pan American Games|Pan American Games]]}} {{MedalBronze| [[Basketball at the 1999 Pan American Games|Winnipeg 1999]] | }} }}
'''Rolando Hourruitiner''' (born May 28, 1975) is a [[business]] [[professional]] and [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneur]]; focusing mainly in [[Sports entertainment|sports]] & [[entertainment]], [[Media (communication)|media]], [[Digital media|digital]], [[Mobile app|mobile]] and [[Hospitality industry|hospitality]]. Hourruitiner is a former [[basketball]] [[Player (game)|player]], [[coach (sport)|coach]] and [[sports agent]] with extensive international exposure. He has also been featured as a basketball TV commentator and analyst in Puerto Rico.
Rolando was a member of the [[Puerto Rico national basketball team|Puerto Rico Basketball National Team]] from 1995 until 2004, including been a key player of the 2004 team that defeated the [[USA Basketball|United States Basketball National Team]] at the [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2004 Olympic Games]] in [[Athens]], [[Greece]].<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ho/rolando-hourruitiner-1.html Rolando Hourruitiner]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabasketball.com/seniormen/2004/04_moly1_box.html|title=Puerto Rico 92, USA 73|date=|publisher=Usabasketball.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101085351/http://www.usabasketball.com/seniormen/2004/04_moly1_box.html|archivedate=November 1, 2011|deadurl=yes|accessdate=December 18, 2011|df=}}</ref> He also competed in [[Pan American Games|PanAm Games]], [[Goodwill Games]] and [[FIBA World Cup]].
Hourruitiner graduated from [[Charleston Southern University]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[South Carolina|SC]], in 1998. He was co-captain of the 1996-1997 [[CSU Buccaneers]] [[NCAA Division I|NCAA Division 1]] basketball team that won the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Big South Conference]] championship and went on to the [[1997 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1997 NCAA Basketball Tournament]]. It was the first time for Charleston Southern University Basketball to compete in the National Tournament... To this day, it's still the only CSU Bucs team to make it.
In October, 2015, Rolando was inducted into the Sports Hall of Fame of his hometown [[Caguas, Puerto Rico|Caguas]], [[Puerto Rico]] (Pabellón de la Fama del Deporte Cagüeño). He was honored and recognized for his years of continued success as a basketball player, coach and executive, including his 10 years (1995-2004) as a member of the Puerto Rico Basketball National Team.
